s with authorization2star  aBy focusing on how the idea of heroism on the battlefield helped construct, perpetuate, and challenge racial and gender hierarchies in the United States between World War I and the present, Warring over Valor provides fresh perspectives on the history of American military heroism. The book offers two major insights into the history of military heroism. First, it reveals a precarious ambiguity in the efforts of minorities such as African Americans, Asian Americans, Native Americans, women, and gay men to be recognized as heroic soldiers. Paradoxically, America’s heroism discourse allowed them to press their case for full membership in the nation, but doing so simultaneously validated the dichotomous interpretations of race and gender they repudiated. The ambiguous role of marginalized groups in war-related hero-making processes also testifies to this volume’s second general insight: the durability and tenacity of the masculine warrior hero in U.S. society and culture. Warring over Valor bridges a gap in the historiography of heroism and military affairs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aArmed ForcesxMinorities. 0aHeroesxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aHeroesxHistoryx21st centuryxUnited States. 0aHeroeszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aHeroeszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aHeroes. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  awar, valor, race, gender, American, military, heroism, United States, Asian Americans, African Americans, Native Americans, women, gay men, masculine, hero.1 aAndersen, Carrie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndersen, Carrie.1 aEstes, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEstes, Steve.1 aHall, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct